[1]Design and développementConçu by the Società Idrovolanti Alta Italia (RAIS) as a smaller version of S. 12, the S. 13 was a flying boat biplane single-engine reconnaissance and hunting.
[2]It had a crew of two seated side-by-side behind a single windscreen; the observer had a machine gun for training purposes.
[3]The seaplane was powered by a single V6 engine Isotta Fraschini 250&#x20;ch.Emile Taddéoli, a pioneer of aviation in switzerland and later the head pilot of Ad Astra Aero, from Switzerland to Sesto Calende, where he was hired as test pilot for Savoia in mid-1914.
[4]Over the following five years, Taddéoli realized more than 2,700 flight tests, flying about 150,000 kilometres (93,000 &#x20;mi).
[5]In January 1919 Emile Taddéoli was the first rider crossed lesApennins in a seaplane between Sesto Calende and San Remo.
[6]On July 12, 1919, with a passenger on board, it flew from Calende on leLac Major up to Lake Geneva in 110 minutes, flying over the Mont-Blanc (4,695 meters (15,404&#x20;ft))in its RAIS S. 13.
[7]The Italian Navy took delivery of 12 aircraft in 1919, but the plane was also exported to Japan, Norway, Spain, Sweden and Yugoslavia.
[8]In France, the S. 13 was built under license as the CAMS C-13, and in Spain the workshops naval Barcelona built also seven copies under license.A single-seat version, the S. 13 Tipo, was ordered by the Italian Navy, but this order was later cancelled to focus on the Macchi M. 7.
